The transformation not only beautified the historic Selma to Montgomery March Trail, it blazed a new trail in West Montgomery. https://t.co/YQxnWbE8j7

Kevin founded The King's Canvas in 2017 with a mission to provide local artists the free studio space, opportunities, and access needed for their talents to thrive.

Through The Progress Project by Hyundai, our Team Members in Montgomery nominated him to receive a $15,000 grant. https://t.co/QPgtDfOIaO

There, the nonprofit‚Äôs founder, Kevin King, painted a tribute to his studio‚Äôs location along the historic Selma to Montgomery March Trail. The colorful mural instantly united the local community. But Kevin had bigger plans for the outdoor space around it. https://t.co/qjapaKKiSq

Introducing @CanvasMGM, the third of three Black-owned local businesses we helped support through The Progress Project by Hyundai.

Montgomery is a city rich with history‚Äìone that‚Äôs depicted in a mural painted on the side of The King‚Äôs Canvas art studio in West Montgomery. üßµ https://t.co/JMMd7KoviG

Text:
Learn more about The Progress Project by Hyundai: https://t.co/x5gEGpHpQP  

Stay tuned in the coming weeks as we highlight the final business nominated. https://t.co/j3YjjPNwSR

Now, Ida plans to hire more local people in the community. And to continue her personal mission of donating a slice of comfort to all those in need.

See more about JoZettie‚Äôs Cupcakes here: https://t.co/CL36XBQigs https://t.co/1nPfKBunra

Through The Progress Project by Hyundai, our Team Members at Hyundai Motor Manufacturing Alabama nominated JoZettie's Cupcakes to receive a grant of $15,000 to go towards her business. With the funds, she was able to purchase a new industrial oven, mixer, and install new floors. https://t.co/9P50Rzn8S3

Locals can‚Äôt get enough. So much so, that she expanded to a second location. But with the growth, came the growing pains. The cost of supplies was up and she couldn‚Äôt afford new kitchen equipment. Instead, she had to shuttle baked goods between the locations multiple times a day. https://t.co/7fQun3wbEb

Now, Ida has been baking 40 years and is the proud owner of JoZettie‚Äôs Cupcakes, a family-owned bakery in Montgomery, Alabama. There, she serves generational recipes like her grandmother‚Äôs pound cake, made from memory, as well as pies, cakes, and cupcakes all baked from scratch. https://t.co/71AbHV38Qa

But try as she might, she couldn‚Äôt get the recipes to turn out right. So she got to work, adjusting through trial and error until the recipes were perfect. In time, the self-taught baker became the district‚Äôs sought-after pastry chef, and went on to work at a world-famous bakery. https://t.co/1tnYFoJkkb

Get to know @JoZetties Cupcakes‚Äìthe second of three Black-owned businesses in Montgomery we helped support with The Progress Project by Hyundai.

At the age of 24, Ida took her first job as a baker. She had no experience baking, and was only instructed to ‚Äúfollow the recipes.‚Äù üßµ https://t.co/548mFAx7Xn

Text:
Learn more about The Progress Project by Hyundai: https://t.co/x5gEGpHpQP

Stay tuned in the coming weeks as we highlight two more Black-owned businesses that were nominated. https://t.co/En7Da3y1sl

‚Ä¶refreshing the interior, adding storage, and updating the counter. Now, Dr. Quebe feels the same pride for her restaurant as she does the homemade dishes served there. Check out the transformation in the photos, and see more about Plant Bae here: https://t.co/Kjxp61vjrp https://t.co/T1SIn0d631

Plant Bae was one of three local businesses that received a $15,000 grant to go towards building up the business. With the funds from The Progress Project by Hyundai, Dr. Quebe was able to achieve the needed updates at the restaurant‚Äìincluding installing new flooring‚Ä¶ https://t.co/4VCAlXKYJ7

So we stepped in to help. The Team Members at Hyundai Motor Manufacturing Alabama in Montgomery nominated Plant Bae to receive support through The Progress Project by Hyundai, an initiative to celebrate Black History and help support Black-owned businesses in the community. https://t.co/aG1E9BdXOn

‚ÄúAnd with that being said, I‚Äôll be opening Plant Bae vegan restaurant May 8th, 2020.‚Äù That video got 50,000 views. And Plant Bae quickly won the hearts and stomachs of locals and tourists. But despite the restaurant's success, Dr. Quebe felt the space‚Äôs appearance was lacking. https://t.co/OmVHALYfKo

But she stood in front of the restaurant's apple-inspired logo and the apple trees she and her daughters had planted, and recorded a video on her phone. ‚ÄúMartin Luther King Jr. once said, even if I knew the world would go to pieces, I still would plant my apple tree,‚Äù she quoted. https://t.co/Sb44uz4X1T

Get to know #PlantBae‚Äìthe first of three Black-owned businesses we helped support with The Progress Project by Hyundai.

On the day she announced the opening of her restaurant, Dr. Quebe didn‚Äôt know what to expect. It was the middle of the pandemic in Montgomery, Alabama. üßµ https://t.co/AgLW6TIDE3
